<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match the Salmon Preparation to Wine Structure</strong> - Wild salmon's leaner texture and mineral finish pairs beautifully with crisp whites like Sancerre or Chablis, while farmed salmon's higher fat content demands wines with more body and acidity like Oregon Pinot Noir or white Burgundy. The omega-3 oils in salmon can make tannic reds taste metallic, so choose softer tannin profiles or stick to whites and light reds.</li>

  <li><strong>Temperature is Critical for Salmon Pairings</strong> - Serve white wines at 45-50°F rather than the typical 40°F when pairing with salmon—the slightly warmer temperature allows the wine's texture to complement the fish's richness without the acidity becoming too sharp. For light reds like Pinot Noir, aim for 55-60°F to prevent the tannins from overwhelming the delicate fish flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Cedar Plank Salmon Calls for Specific Wine Choices</strong> - When salmon is cooked on cedar planks, the wood imparts subtle smoky, resinous notes that pair exceptionally with wines that have seen some oak aging. Try a lightly oaked Chardonnay from Sonoma Coast or a Pinot Noir from Oregon's Dundee Hills—the complementary wood influences create a harmonious bridge between wine and food.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider Salmon's Natural Terroir</strong> - Pacific Northwest salmon pairs naturally with wines from the same region due to shared environmental influences. The mineral-driven acidity in Columbia Valley Riesling or Willamette Valley Pinot Gris echoes the clean, briny qualities of wild Pacific salmon, creating terroir-driven harmony that European wines often can't replicate.</li>

  <li><strong>Decanting Red Wine for Salmon is Usually Unnecessary</strong> - Most red wines suitable for salmon (young Pinot Noir, Beaujolais, Loire Valley reds) benefit from minimal aeration. Instead of decanting, simply open the bottle 15-20 minutes before serving to allow volatile compounds to dissipate without over-aerating delicate fruit flavors that complement the fish.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Both Reds and Whites</strong> - The wider bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates both the delicate aromatics of Pinot Noir and the complex mineral notes of Chardonnay or white Burgundy—the classic salmon wine pairings. This glass shape prevents the wine from overwhelming the subtle flavors of the fish while enhancing the wine's complementary characteristics.</li>

  <li><strong>Fresh is Best for Salmon Wine Pairings</strong> - Avoid heavily aged wines when serving salmon, as the fish's delicate flavors are easily overpowered by developed tertiary aromas. Choose wines under 5 years old for whites and under 8 years for reds. The exception is aged Champagne or Chablis Premier Cru, whose mineral evolution actually enhances smoked or cured salmon preparations.</li>

  <li><strong>Sauce Determines Final Wine Selection</strong> - The wine should ultimately pair with the dominant flavor on the plate. Hollandaise sauce demands high-acid wines like Muscadet or Albariño to cut through the richness, while dill and lemon preparations call for herbaceous wines like Sauvignon Blanc from Loire Valley. For teriyaki-glazed salmon, consider off-dry Riesling from Alsace to balance the sweet-savory complexity.</li>
</ol>





  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with grilled versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops smoky, caramelized flavors that pair beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or robust whites like oaked Chardonnay. Poached salmon retains delicate, clean flavors that complement lighter wines such as Sauvignon Blanc, Albariño, or unoaked Chablis. The cooking method dramatically changes the salmon's texture and intensity, requiring different wine styles to achieve harmony.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine with salmon at room temperature or chilled?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines should be served chilled at 45-50°F to enhance their crisp acidity and complement salmon's richness. Light reds like Pinot Noir benefit from slight chilling to 55-60°F, which prevents the alcohol from overwhelming the fish's delicate flavors. Room temperature service is only recommended for fuller-bodied reds when pairing with heavily seasoned or grilled salmon preparations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine works best with salmon teriyaki or Asian-glazed preparations?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer excel with teriyaki salmon, as their touch of sweetness balances the soy and sugar in the glaze while their acidity cuts through the fish's richness. Alternatively, a fruit-forward Pinot Noir from Oregon or New Zealand complements the umami flavors without competing with the Asian spices. Avoid bone-dry wines that will taste harsh against the sweet-savory glaze.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is wine with salmon a good pairing for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—salmon's moderate flavor intensity and rich texture make it forgiving for wine pairing experiments. The fish's natural oils complement both crisp whites and light reds, giving beginners flexibility to explore different styles. Start with classic pairings like Pinot Grigio or Pinot Noir, then gradually experiment with more complex wines as your palate develops.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibred text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting wines that are too heavy or tannic, which overwhelm salmon's delicate flavor and create an unbalanced pairing. Full-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked Chardonnay can mask the fish entirely. Instead, focus on wines with bright acidity and moderate body that enhance rather than compete with the salmon's natural richness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use the same wine for cooking and serving with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, using the same wine for both cooking and serving creates harmonious flavor integration throughout the meal. Choose a dry white wine like Sauvignon Blanc or Pinot Grigio that you enjoy drinking—the cooking process will concentrate its flavors while the serving portion provides a complementary bridge between the dish and your palate. Avoid cooking wines of poor quality, as their flaws will be magnified in the final dish.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good wine alternatives if I don't like traditional salmon pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If classic Pinot Noir or Chardonnay don't appeal to you, try Grüner Veltliner for its herbaceous complexity, Vermentino for bright minerality, or Gamay for light red fruit without heavy tannins. Champagne or other sparkling wines also work beautifully, as their effervescence and acidity cleanse the palate between bites. These alternatives maintain the necessary balance while offering unique flavor profiles that complement salmon's versatility.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does wild versus farmed salmon affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Wild salmon typically has a firmer texture and more intense, mineral-driven flavor that pairs well with wines showing greater complexity like Burgundian Chardonnay or Loire Valley Sancerre. Farmed salmon tends to be richer and more buttery due to higher fat content, making it ideal for softer, rounder wines such as Viognier or fruit-forward Pinot Noir. The difference in oil content and flavor intensity requires subtle adjustments in wine selection to achieve optimal balance.</p>
